
## Conditional Statements
--> Conditional statements are used to execute different code based on conditions.

## Types of Conditions

1) if Statement
--> Runs code only if condition is true

php id="e5n2yt"
<?php
$x = 10;

if ($x > 5) {
    echo "x is greater than 5";
}
?>

2) if...else Statement
--> Two possible outputs

```php id="f8q1ws"
<?php
$x = 3;

if ($x > 5) {
    echo "Greater";
} else {
    echo "Smaller";
}
?>
```

---

### 3) **else if Statement**

* Used for multiple conditions

```php id="g7k3op"
<?php
$marks = 75;

if ($marks >= 90) {
    echo "Grade A";
}
else if ($marks >= 70) {
    echo "Grade B";
}
else {
    echo "Grade C";
}
?>
```

---

### 4) **switch Statement**

* Used to avoid long if...else chains

```php id="h6z9lm"
<?php
$day = "Monday";

switch($day) {
    case "Monday":
        echo "Start of week";
        break;
    case "Friday":
        echo "Weekend coming";
        break;
    default:
        echo "Normal day";
}
?>
```

---

# 📊 **Final Summary (Important Points)**

* Operators → Perform operations

  * Arithmetic → Math
  * Assignment → Assign values
  * Comparison → Compare values
  * Logical → Combine conditions

* Conditions → Control program flow

  * if → Single condition
  * if...else → Two conditions
  * else if → Multiple conditions
  * switch → Multiple fixed cases

